, R=36 (with orange)\nThe difference is 161 - 26 = 135, which equals O=135. So the orange blocks are being converted to/from white.\nLooking at earlier entries:\nEntry 30: MOUSE on something -> W=157, c=19, O=45, R=18 (no N!)\nEntry 31: MOUSE on something -> W=148, c=19, N=45, R=27 (no O!)\nSo there are two \"modes\":\n1. Mode with N (green frame): N + R vary, no O\n2. Mode with O (orange blocks): O + R vary, no N\nAnd clicking toggles between these modes.\nThe total non-background, non-HUD pixels seem to be:\n- Mode 1: N + R = 144 + 36 = 180 (when frame not covered)\n- Mode 2: O + R = varies\nWhen the white shape covers the green frame, N decreases and W increases. The goal might be to get N to 0 (all green covered).\nLooking at entries 15-21, the lowest N was 45. Let me check if there's a way to get N lower.\nActually, wait. Let me look at entry 30 more carefully:\nEntry 30: W=157, c=19, O=45, R=18 (total non-W, non-c: 63)\nEntry 31: W=148, c=19, N=45, R=27 (total non-W, non-c: 72)\nSo in entry 30, the orange mode has O=45, R=18. And in entry 31, the green mode has N=45, R=27.\nThe key insight is that the white shape (W) covers parts of the frame/blocks, reducing their visible count. The goal is likely to position the white shape to cover as much of the frame/blocks as possible.\nLet me try to get back to the initial state and try a more systematic approach. I need to click on the green frame to toggle back to a state where I can move the white shape.\nWait, looking at entry 60: W=161, N=144, R=36. This has a large white object (161 pixels) and the green frame (144). If I can move this white object to cover the green frame...\nBut I'm currently in entry 64's state: W=27, N=144, O=135, R=36. Let me click on red to toggle to the state without orange.", "kind": "reasoning", "inContext": false}, {"label": "TOOL CALL: python", "content": "<tool_call>\n<function=python>\n<parameter=code>\n# Click on red to toggle to state without orange\nseg = current_frame.segmentation